      <abstract>Soldier from Numa, Iowa, served in the Allied intervention in Russia, 1918-1920, the "Polar Bear Expedition." Collection includes letter written from Archangel to his wife describing cold weather, daily routine, and hopes of returning home.</abstract>
      <unitid countrycode="us" repositorycode="MiU-H" encodinganalog="099" type="call number">86721 Aa 1</unitid>
      <langmaterial>The materials are in <language encodinganalog="041" langcode="eng">English.</language></langmaterial>
      <repository>
        <corpname encodinganalog="852"><subarea>Bentley Historical Library</subarea> University of Michigan</corpname>
        <extptr href="bhladd" show="embed" actuate="onload"/>
      </repository>
    </did>
    <descgrp type="admin">
      <acqinfo encodinganalog="541">
        <p>The collection was donated by Roger L. Heiple, of South Lyon, Michigan, in 1980 (Donor no.: <num type="donor" encodinganalog="541$e">6267</num>).</p>
      </acqinfo>
      <accessrestrict encodinganalog="506">
        <p>The collection is open for research.</p>
      </accessrestrict>
      <prefercite encodinganalog="524">
        <p>item, folder title, box no., Lee J. Ward letter, Bentley Historical Library, University of Michigan</p>
      </prefercite>
    </descgrp>
    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>Resident of <geogname normal="Numa (Iowa)">Numa, Iowa</geogname>, who served with the <corpname normal="United States. Army. Infantry, 339th.">339th Infantry</corpname> during the American intervention in North Russia, 1918-1919.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The <genreform normal="Letters (correspondence)">letter</genreform>, a photocopy, describes the weather in <geogname normal="Arkhangel'sk (Russia)">Archangel</geogname>, his daily routine, and his hopes of going home. The original is owned by <persname normal="Heiple, Roger L.">Roger L. Heiple</persname>, <geogname normal="South Lyon (Mich.)">South Lyon, Mich.</geogname></p>
    </scopecontent>
